data.content:
Here's the approach — two pieces:

### `GlobalExceptionHandler.cs`
Implements `IExceptionHandler` (ASP.NET Core 8+). A `switch` expression maps exception types → status codes. Client errors (4xx) include `exception.Message`; 500s return a generic message so no internals leak. All exceptions are logged.

### Wire-up in `Program.cs`
```csharp
builder.Services.AddProblemDetails();
builder.Services.AddExceptionHandler<GlobalExceptionHandler>();
// ...
app.UseExceptionHandler();
```

**How it works:** The `UseExceptionHandler` middleware catches any exception, delegates to your `IExceptionHandler`, and the response is a standard RFC 7807 JSON body like:

```json
{ "status": 404, "title": "Not Found", "detail": "Item 42 was not found." }
```

No `try-catch` in endpoints — just throw the appropriate exception and the middleware handles the rest.

> **Note:** If you're on ASP.NET Core 7 (not 8+), `IExceptionHandler` isn't available. Use custom middleware with `app.UseExceptionHandler(...)` and an error-handling lambda instead. Let me know if you need that variant.
